recurrent motifs in Northern literature.The essays in Myths, Legends, and Heroes include an examination of the theme of sibling rivalry, an analysis of Christ's unusual ride into hell as found in both Old Norse and Old English, a discussion of Beowulf's swimming prowess and an analysis of the poetry in Snorri Sturluson's Edda. A tribute to Durham University professor John McKinnell's distinguished contributions to the field, this volume offers new insights in light of linguistic and archaeological evidence and a broad range of study with regard to both chronology and methodology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 4aDISCOUNT-B. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh1 aAnlezark, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnlezark, Daniel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAshurst, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDamico, Helen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFinlay, Alison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHill, Joyce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJesch, Judith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLarrington, Carolyne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcturk, Rory, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoss, Margaret Clunies, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRuggerini, Maria Elena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSimek, Rudolf, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144266205640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442662056423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442662056.j